<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-324-418  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 324 418.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 9 1990 n295 p48(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Analysts: here comes fiber. (fiber optics)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilde, Candee.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber optics deployed to the home is seen to be a maintechnological trend of the 1990s.andP;  This technology is beingfacilitated by vendors and planned by regional Bell holdingcompanies.andP;  The fiber-based user interface brought into the homewould deliver quality voice transmission as well as a rich rangeof interactive switched digital video, broadband datatransmissions and other services, creating what one analyst callsthe 'smart home.' All seven RBOCs are proceeding with plans todeploy the fiber optics technology.andP;  Key issues at this pointinvolve cost of cabling, transmission costs and the expectedeasing of restrictions on the telephone companies' ability tobring television signals into the home.andP;  Raynet Corp (Menlo Park,CA) recently announced its Local Optical Carrier technology, whichis expected to encourage fiber deployment by reducing the cost oftransmission.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Raynet Corp. (product development).andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsBell Regional Holding CompaniesCost of CommunicationsMarketing StrategyIntegrated Voice-DataUser InterfaceIntelligent BuildingsCommunications TechnologyPlanning.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Measuring Bells' progress in fiber optic deployment. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>